Polynomials are functions like lines, parabolas, cubics, etc. The best
examples to consider are horizontal lines and parabolas.

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  No horizontal line crosses the \emph{x}-axis.
\end{itemize}

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH110/December_2012/MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2d_horizontal_line.jpg}

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  The graph of a parabola can be shifted so that it doesn't cross the
  \emph{x}-axis.
\end{itemize}

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH110/December_2012/MER_MATH110_December_2012_Question_2d_parabola.jpg}

Either of these would be a counter-example, so the statement is false.
